  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a complex string/bitstring problem involving prefix-free properties and minimizing length. It requires constructing a set of bitstrings such that no string is a prefix of another, even when truncated, which relates to Huffman coding or prefix-free codes under specific constraints.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "prefix_analysis_helper",
      "instructions": "Analyze the given set of reported bitstring IDs to identify the maximum length of any ID and the structure of the existing prefixes. Determine if any existing ID is a prefix of another, as this would violate the core requirement."
    },
    {
      "label": "combinatorial_construction_helper",
      "instructions": "Given the constraints of the bitstring IDs and the truncation rule, determine the minimum length required for the extended bitstrings to ensure that no ID can be mistaken for another. Focus on the properties of a prefix-free code (like a Huffman tree or a complete binary tree) where the leaves represent the IDs."
    },
    {
      "label": "optimization_helper",
      "instructions": "Calculate the total length of the extended bitstrings. If the goal is to minimize the total length or the maximum length, apply a greedy approach or a dynamic programming approach to assign bitstrings to the existing IDs such that the prefix-free property is maintained with minimal cost."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the prefix analysis to understand the current constraints, use the combinatorial construction to build a valid prefix-free set, and apply the optimization logic to ensure the resulting bitstrings meet the problem's specific minimization criteria."
}

